<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900808-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>900808-0022.</DOCID><HL>   End to Antitrust Exemption   On Airline Fares Is Urged</HL><DATE>08/08/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Justice Department urged the Departmentof Transportation to rescind the antitrust exemption underwhich U.S. airlines participate in fare-setting forinternational flights.   The department said that the fare-setting practices of theGeneva-based International Air Transport Association, thetrade group for the major world airlines, areanti-competitive and result in higher fares.</LP><TEXT>   IATA's members, acting under a grant of antitrust immunityfirst granted in 1946 by the U.S. government, hold tariffconferences to set fares. In 1985, the DOT extended theexemption, but said it would review the policy in five years.The Justice Department's recommendation was in response toIATA's application for a renewed exemption.   The recommendation wasn't unexpected. The JusticeDepartment had sought to end the exemption in the late 1970sand early 1980s, according to Bert Rein, one of IATA'sWashington attorneys. &quot;The aeronautical experts rejected it,&quot;he said.   The Transportation Department declined to comment on thefiling.</TEXT></DOC>